<DOC><DOCNO> AP900820-0189 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-PX-08-20-90 1705EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Soviet-Oil     08-20 0223</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Soviet-Oil,0231</SECOND><HEAD>Say Russian Republic Wants to Join OPEC</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Russia's foreign economics minister said Mondaythe Soviet Union's largest republic would like to join OPEC.   Viktor Yaroshenko told a news conference that the republicconsidered itself free to join such organizations because of itsassertion of independence of central Soviet control. The republic'sparliament has decided that it _ and not Soviet authorities _control the resources on Russia's territory.   ``We are prepared to enter as one of the members of OPEC, nowperhaps as an observer but in the future, if we are accepted, toenter fully,'' Yaroshenko told reporters gathered in Russia'sSupreme Soviet chambers.   It wasn't clear how the 13-member Organization of PetroleumExporting Countries would respond to an application, if it receivedone. The cartel produces a substantial portion of the West's energyneeds.   The Russian government is now headed by Ivan Silayev, areform-minded leader who works closely with Boris N. Yeltsin, therepublic's president.   They are trying to generate foreign currency to help solve direeconomic problems, and the republic's oil is one potential revenuesource.   Most of the Soviet Union's oil is located in Russia. The countryas a whole produces about 12.1 million barrels daily, making it oneof the world's leading producers. But much of that oil is consumeddomestically.</TEXT></DOC>